oses a more reciprocal model of ekphrasis that involves an encounter or exchange between visual and textual cultures. This critical and theoretical shift demands a new form of ekphrastic poetics, which is less concerned with representational and institutional struggles, and more concerned with ideas of ethics, affect and intersubjectivity. Ekphrastic encounters brings together leading scholars working in the field of word-and-image studies and offers a fresh exploration of ekphrastic texts from the Renaissance to the present day. Taken together, the chapters establish a new set of theoretical frameworks for exploring the ekphrastic encounter.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArt and literature. 0aEkphrasis. 4aLiterature Studies 2020. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aAffect.  aEkphrasis.  aEthics.  aIconotext.  aIntermedial.  aLessing.  aRepresentation.  aShakespeare.  aparagone.  aut pictura poesis.1 aCheeke, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClüver, Claus, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEisendrath, Rachel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeffernan, James A. W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKennedy, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKennedy, David, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLawrence, Jason, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLouvel, Liliane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacLeod, Catriona, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMalt, Johanna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcDonald, Keith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.